Homework 1

Brooke Wills

February 14, 2017

Below I define the quadratic equation in R using the funciton quad().

quad <- function(x,a=0,b=0,c=0) {
  a*x^2+b*x+c
}
x <- seq(from=-10, to=10, by=.1)

a <- quad(x,a=3)
a2 <- quad(x,a=2)
a3 <- quad(x,a=1)
a4 <- quad(x,a=-1)
a5 <- quad(x,a=-2)

b <- quad(x,b=3)
b2 <- quad(x,b=2)
b3 <- quad(x,b=1)
b4 <- quad(x,b=-1)
b5 <- quad(x,b=-2)

c <- quad(x,c=3)
c2 <- quad(x,c=2)
c3 <- quad(x,c=1)
c4 <- quad(x,c=-1)
c5 <- quad(x,c=-2)

ab <- quad(x,a=3,b=1)
ab2 <- quad(x,a=2,b=-3)
ab3 <- quad(x,a=1,b=5)
ab4 <- quad(x,a=-1,b=2)
ab5 <- quad(x,a=-2,b=-5)

ac <- quad(x,a=3,c=1)
ac2 <- quad(x,a=2,c=-3)
ac3 <- quad(x,a=1,c=5)
ac4 <- quad(x,a=-1,c=2)
ac5 <- quad(x,a=-2,c=-5)

bc <- quad(x,b=3,c=1)
bc2 <- quad(x,b=2,c=-3)
bc3 <- quad(x,b=1,c=5)
bc4 <- quad(x,b=-1,c=2)
bc5 <- quad(x,b=-2,c=-5)

The plots below each show the effects of different values for the constants in the quadratic formula Ax^2+Bx+C and the other constants set to zero. When A is the only non zero number we get a curve with varying widths. When B is the only constant we see only lines at different angels and when C is the only constant we see horizontal lines paralell to the x axis.
